taxonomicNotes: The Holotype of this species was collected together with Paratopotypes by Robert Miller and others in February 1976 from the Río (Potrero) Grande, about 9.6km W of the town of Ameca. Several Paratypes go back to collections from the type location in 1957 and 1971, one single male to a collection of R. Vrijenhoek and M. Douglas from a bridge over the Río Ameca (precisely: Río Cuisillos), 1km E of the estación Pacana, SE of the Presa La Vega, in 1981. No subpopulations are distinguished.

Clianthus puniceus, following decisions reached by Heenan (2000) is treated as a separate species from C. magnificus based on minor foliage and floral differences. These were summarized by de Lange (2023) who noted that C. puniceus has mat-green foliage, and an upper leaf surface that is often slightly glaucous in colour. C. magnificus leaves are dark green, and the upper leaf surface very glossy. C. puniceus flowers are slightly smaller, the standard is conspicuously striped white, and the spur blotched or striped white as well. C. magnificus flowers are larger, very dark red, blotched dark purple-black near the base (very rarely with a few faint white stripes) and the spur is uniformly dark red.

However, mostly unpublished genetic studies show little difference between these two species, and Song et al. (2008) based on their molecular studies suggested that northern Tairawhiti populations (Clianthus magnificus) had the same sequence as C. puniceus from Moturemu, Kaipara Harbour. Nevertheless, for now they are maintained as distinct species.
This species was previously included in the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).

Hemignathus lucidus, H. hanapepe and H. affinis (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as H. lucidus following AOU (1998 & supplements); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993).

Govenia floridana was initially identified as the more widespread tropical species Govenia utriculata when discovered in 1957. However, the Florida population differs from G. utriculata in that the sheaths are not inflated, it is nearly polygonal in cross section, the column is prominently winged, and the petals are spotted (Greenwood 1991). Based on these differences, Govenia floridana was established as a distinct species by Brown (2000).
Hypotaenidia wakensis (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Gallirallus. Monotypic.
Zapornia palmeri (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Porzana.

Psephotellus pulcherrimus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Psephotus.
Himatione sanguinea and H. fraithii (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as H. sanguinea following AOU (1998 & supplements); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993).
